  "text": "In breast cancer, resistance to standard-of-care systemic adjuvant treatments such as endocrine and chemotherapies remains a major health burden and prompts the need for novel therapeutic targets for patients with advanced, unresponsive, or relapsed disease. We previously used gene-expression profiles of breast tumors to identify extracellular/secretory proteins and cell surfacereceptor genes whose high expression levels associate with poor clinical end points. For example, we recently identified serine protease inhibitor Kazal-type 1 (SPINK1) as an important therapeutic target in breast cancer by using a combined genotype and phenotype screening approach. We found that inhibition of SPINK1 by neutralizing antibodies curtailed multiple aggressive properties, including cell survival, invasiveness, and chemoresistance [CITATION_1] . A second candidate identified in the same study was the phosphatidylserine receptor (PTDSR).",
